
[1]slough

   SLOUGH, n. slou.

   1. A place of deep mud or mire; a hole full of mire.

   2. [pron. sluff.] The skin or cast skin of a serpent. [Its use for the
   skin in general, in Shakespeare, is not authorized.]

   3. [pron. sluff.] The part that separates from a foul sore. The dead
   part which separates from the living in mortification.

    SLOUGH, v.i. sluff. To separate from the sound flesh; to come off; as
                 the matter over a sore; a term in surgery.
